      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my physics midterm and im kinda stuck on entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what quantum entanglement actually is? also how is it different from just regular classical correlation? thx",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become linked such that the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, regardless of the distance separating them. It is fundamentally different from classical correlation because in classical systems, properties are usually already determined (hidden variables) before measurement, whereas in quantum mechanics, the properties remain undefined until measured, and the correlation cannot be explained by any local hidden variable theory as proven by Bell's Theorem. This \"spooky action at a distance\" defies our everyday intuition about how objects interact locally in the universe.\n\nTo help you study, remember that entanglement allows for instantaneous correlations that exceed classical limits, which is why it is a cornerstone for quantum computing and cryptography. While classical correlation is like two coins that always land on the same side because they were set up that way, entanglement is like two coins that have no fixed side until they are flipped, yet they always match perfectly. This distinction is crucial for understanding why quantum mechanics behaves so differently from classical physics.\n\nIf you need to review specific equations or experiment setups regarding entanglement, let me know, and I can provide those details. Just keep in mind that while the math gets complex quickly, the core",
